From my experience, we the people choose who becomes great in our culture. 
Often we choose through the lenses of celebrity, or power/greatness is chosen to give to someone because they have excessive large amounts of money. 
These things money,fame, and fortune can really attach to the ego and shift who we show up as to the world. 
How much of our ego do we get to keep? How do we know when to use the ego to create greatness and how do we know when let go of it to be a good man?
Also who decides what a good man even is?

January 17, 2016- 
The second Ariel asked me this question- I had 1 million visions: 1 million pictures and 1 million moments of the 3.5 years of ACL reconstruction, hand surgeries, quad tear. Plus the on and offs -promoting of the division that got to do what I loved, while I sat out and watched them on Fox Sports. 

During those mentally challenging times, what I realized was the thoughts/mentality that got me healthy the fastest was when I finally surrendered to what was. 

I surrendered to the outcome and let myself enjoy my life without fighting for those moments. 

I was able to be in gratitude for the life I had already built as it was. 

Getting to fight was the cherry on top of this life. In that moment of the interview, I realized life was amazing before I had won the belt. 

Sometimes in life I’ve gotten distracted by focusing outside of myself to find my happiness -a belt, a car, a girl…always something separate from me. 

After winning the title once, I was still searching for something big…

After winning it the second time, getting through all those injuries, all within a 3-1/2 year period, I realized being happy and in gratitude without the belt and the career was the key to having it all. 

Things could just happen naturally, because I wasn’t trying to control the outcomes anymore. I got to do the work and keep the faith 🙏

On the cusp of watching a big title fight this weekend, I look forward to seeing two championship fighters. Their hard work, blood and sweat create an impressive war to spectate. Excited to hear and learn what realizations these champs come to while on their own respective title runs at the same time 🏆

Yup, I fought a ninja 🥷 

Since it’s Ninja Day, thought it was cool to share this story that comes up occasionally…

I was six weeks out of my fight with Ian Mccall, preparing to fight in SD at the San Diego Sports Arena. This guy came in to the gym when I was not there and put money on the line to say that he could beat the best champion out of that gym, who was in his weight class.

Since I was preparing for a fight already-my manager at the time asked me if I’d be willing to spar this guy 

I beat the hell out of him on the ground to the finish in the 1st round. After that, he stood up and said “of course you won,because you took me down to the ground.” 

He obviously still had some fight left in him and I needed more work anyways -so I said, would you like a second round with no takedowns?  he said yes -that’s why we stood back up and then he got TKO’d and I got a great test of nerves + a little rent $ before a fight. 🙌 #NinjaOut #InternationalNinjaDay
